+Félix Isaí Dz A I know for a fact that Mexico city is sitting on a deep 
alluvial deposit from a historic lake. And I know that alluvial deposits 
like most soils amplify outcrop intensity. Earthquake engineering is what I 
do for living. I have studied the 1985 Mexico city Earthquake.

Buildings are very expensive because this lake deposit resonates at roughly 
3 seconds. Just enough to double resonate buildings 7-20 stories tall. 

The fact that there is no damage is not because of the alarm systems you 
are referring to. It is because of good design and money well spent. My 
argument is that alarms are useless, unless we are talking about a Tsunami 
(in which case evacuation is a huge deal).

+amirali223 Not the case for Mexico City. Remember the city is over a lake. 
The waves are amplified, strong enough for damage. Alert can advice and let 
people be prepared.
A building can be strong but less damage can hurt and kill people (only in 
a broken window can hurt you).

It is very hard for Mexico City, because building any structure is very 
expensive, not just because of earthquakes, we have to build over a lake. 
Any building can fail in this conditions and anything can be usefull for 
saving lives, that includes an alarm.

In any case, Mexico is doing it well. 7.8 Richter Earthquake in one of the 
most populated areas in America, zero deceased and only 4 injured. Just few 
countrys can say that.

Some areas in the USA can be seriously damaged by less strong earthquakes.

+Félix Isaí Dz A Earthquake primary waves travel at 7 km / sec and 
Earthquake secondary waves travel at 3 km / sec. The most damaging 
Earthquakes are the ones that occur nearby. There is  no time for alarms. 
An earthquake hundreds of kilometres away will provide time for alarms but 
the shaking will have dissipated by the time it reaches you.  

The best way to prepare is to design good building and spend good money on 
infrastructure that can withstand Earthquakes. That's the only solution.

+sawankesh There is an alert in Mexico City, the alert sounds 1 minute 
before the earthquake arrives to the city.
In many buildings the instrucction for people in 1 to 3rd floors is going 
out, and stay for the 4th floor and upper.

But each building has its own plan in case of earthquake, you have to ask 
for the plan when you start living or working in some building or wait for 
the next earthquake simulation.

You don't have time to do much. Based on my personal experience, it 
actually takes you 3-5 seconds to realize an Earthquake is even happening. 
It's best to hide under a solid desk or stand in between a door frame. Just 
to avoid getting hit by falling debris.
